Schmidt is the real problem now for Ireland. McCloskey dropped even as he had a good first outing. This season he's made line-break after line break and run through the Saracens and Toulouse defences twice. Meanwhile Gilroy is still scoring solo tries from 70 metres out - beating five men on the way. But it's not just Schmidt's conservative selection - and incomprehensible failure to bring on badly needed new blood in the backs - but his futile tactics. Against England it was infuriating to watch the backs stand off and let the English team run at them making 40 metres every time. So much for the outdated drift defence. By contrast, the Irish backs were under immediate pressure every time from quick English line speed. Then we have the mindless forward impact play with no offloads - predictable, lacking skill and creativity. It's so easy to defend against. What are the bloody backs for if we don't use them in attacking situations?



